The European "Green Deal"
NEW YORK – Europe has done it.
The European Commission's "Green Deal" announced is to date the first global sustainable development plan decided by a major region of the planet.
It thus becomes a landmark for the entire world – a guide to the transformation toward a prosperous, socially inclusive, and ecologically sustainable economy, a first agenda for all to achieve this.
Of course, the task that lies ahead for the Europeans is impressive.
Even the reading of the documents just made public is overwhelming: at first glance, a profusion of plans, consultations, regulatory frameworks, laws, budgets, and diplomacy, a large number of related topics ranging from energy to transportation, from food to industry.
Its critics will mock European bureaucracy.
But it is a bureaucracy in the best Weberian sense: it is rational.
The sustainable development goals are clearly stated, targets are defined based on objectives subject to timelines, and programs and procedures are tailored to these targets.
Globally, the declared ambition is to achieve carbon neutrality (net zero greenhouse gas emissions) by 2050, to establish a circular economy that puts an end to destructive plastic and petrochemical pollution, pesticides, and toxic waste, and to implement a "farm-to-table" food system that does not kill people by making them eat overly processed industrial products or kill the earth with unsustainable agricultural practices.
And the European Commission understands that the method for achieving this must rely on citizens themselves.
Again, its critics will view the announcements of public consultations as mere show for empty promises.
But talk of idle chatter to French President Emmanuel Macron, who has been facing protests turning to riots for over a year, or to Chilean President Sebastián Piñera, whose country erupted in uprising this autumn following a slight increase in metro ticket prices.
Macron and Piñera are both convinced of the necessity of ecological change.
Both have committed to carbon neutrality for their countries by 2050.
And both are desperately trying to organize or structure a public consultation, but too late.
The American advocates of neoliberalism will once again mock this, claiming that the "market" will know how to address climate change.
But just look at today's United States.
If neoliberalism treats the planet as it has treated American infrastructure, we all have reason to be concerned.
Arriving at an airport in the United States means having to deal with broken elevators, malfunctioning moving walkways, stranded shuttle buses, taxis that don't show up, non-existent rail connections, highways in such poor condition that they're barely passable, replaced by detours.
The reason for these malfunctions is simple: corruption.
Each American election cycle now costs over 8 billion dollars, and financing comes from billionaires, major oil companies, the military-industrial complex, the healthcare industry lobby, and interest groups determined to lower taxes and protect the status quo at all costs.
The solutions provided by the market are a joke when politics is subject to all the influences that emanate from it, as is the case in the United States.
The European Green Deal shows a government as it should be, not one subordinate to corporate interests.
The European Green Deal actually demonstrates the success of European social democracy (in its operational rather than narrowly partisan sense).
A mixed economy, combining markets, state regulatory power, public sector, and civil society, will pursue a mixed strategy: public objectives, public investments in infrastructure, private investments in industrial transformation, research and development missions based on public-private partnerships, and an informed population.
In fact, it is the most sophisticated industrial policy at its level.
(I recently outlined, in broad terms, what a social-democratic Green New Deal strategy would be for the United States.)
We have reasons to be optimistic.
The most important point is that the advanced technologies, which will enable the creation of an advanced decarbonized, resource-efficient, and therefore ecologically sustainable economy, already exist at the commercial or pre-commercial stage.
By combining renewable energy, digital technologies, cutting-edge materials, and collaborative economics in transportation or other infrastructure, we can decarbonize the energy system, transition to a circular economy, and drastically reduce primary resource flows.
But for this, three major challenges must be overcome.
The first challenge is to overcome the interests that seek to maintain the status quo.
The major oil companies will have to absorb the losses, but workers in the sector and mining regions should receive compensation, in the form of income support, retraining, and other public aids.
The plan claims justly a "just transition."
The second challenge is that of financing.
Europe, as well as other world regions, will need to redirect a relatively small portion of its production, around 1% to 2%, towards the green economy, particularly for new infrastructure, public procurement, research and development, industrial equipment renewal, and so on. The financing will come from the private sector as well as public budgets.
Europe must stand up to ideologues who oppose an increase in EU spending.
The facts must be taken into account.
The last major challenge is diplomatic.
Europe accounts for about 9.1% of global carbon dioxide emissions, compared to 30% for China and 14% for the United States.
Even if Europe manages to implement its Green Deal in full, it will be in vain if other world regions do not join its efforts.
Therefore, European leaders rightly consider that diplomacy is fundamental to the success of the Green Deal.
Let's take the example of China.
After decades of rapid growth, which eliminated mass poverty, China has become the world's largest CO2 emitter (although its per capita emissions remain half those of the United States).
China alone will determine the future of the global climate.
On one hand, Chinese leaders know that their country is extremely vulnerable to climate change and risks diplomatic isolation if they do not make sufficient efforts to decarbonize; on the other hand, they must confront the dangers of the inadvertent cold war launched by America.
Hard-line officials within the government and Chinese coal lobbies resist decarbonization, especially since Trump rejects it himself, despite pressure from the United States.
European diplomacy can make a difference if it refuses to subscribe to America's covert measures to hinder China and instead offers this country a clear and positive partnership: working together to establish sustainable infrastructure, development, and technology in Eurasia, within the framework of a Chinese Green Deal comparable to Europe's.
Such a partnership would be immensely beneficial for Europe, China, and the dozen or so Eurasian countries that separate them, not to mention the world as a whole.
Europe has taken a historic step with its ambitious, inspiring, and achievable plan.
The Green Deal is a powerful signal of hope in a world of uncertainties and instability.
